'''William Tharp''' ([[November 27]] [[1803]] &ndash; [[January 9]] [[1865]]) was an [[United States |American]] [[farmer]] and [[politician]] from [[Milford, Delaware |Milford]], in [[Kent County, Delaware |Kent County]], [[Delaware]]. He was a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States) |Democratic Party]], who served in the [[Delaware General Assembly]] and as [[Governor of Delaware]]. 

==Early Life and Family==
Tharp was born [[November 27]] [[1803]] in [[Farmington, Delaware |Farmington]], [[Delaware]], son of James and Eunice Fleming Tharp. His great grandfather had settled near [[Frankford, Delaware]] in [[1735]]. He married Mary A. Johnson, and they had five children: Ruth, Mary Elizabeth, Martina, Williamina, and Ann Purnell. It was through his wife that he inherited his first home on [[U.S. Highway 13]] at [[Farmington, Delaware |Farmington]]. When he was elected [[Governor of Delaware |Governor]] they moved to [[Milford, Delaware |Milford]] and lived at the northeast corner of Church and Front Streets. They were members of Christ [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America |Episcopal Church]] in [[Milford, Delaware |Milford]]. 

==Political career==
Tharp was elected to the [[Delaware State Senate]] and served in the 1839/40 and 1841/42 sessions. He sought reelection to the [[Delaware State Senate |State Senate]] in 1842, but after a months long recount, was found to have lost by 1 vote. He then ran for [[Governor of Delaware |Governor]] in 1844, but lost again to the [[Whig Party (United States) |Whig Party]] candidate, [[Thomas Stockton]]. He ran again in 1846, and was finally elected, by defeating [[Peter F. Causey]], the [[Whig Party (United States) |Whig Party]] candidate. He served as [[Governor of Delaware |Governor]] from [[January 19]] [[1847]] until [[January 21]] [[1851]]. 

Following his term, Tharp continued his agricultural businesses and in 1852, was Treasurer of the [[Pennsylvania Railroad |Delaware Railroad]].

==Death and Legacy==
Tharp died [[January 9]] [[1865]] at [[Milford, Delaware |Milford]], [[Delaware]], and is buried there, at the Christ [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America |Episcopal Church]] Cemetery. He was the grandfather of future [[Governor of Delaware]] [[William T. Watson]].

==Public offices==
Elections are held the first Tuesday after November 1st. Members of the [[Delaware General Assembly]] took office the first Tuesday of January. [[Delaware Senate |State Senators]] have a four year term. The [[Governor of Delaware |Governor]] takes office the third Tuesday of January and has a four year term. 

